Homework 4: Hypothesis testing - Solution

Question 1

A researcher hypothesises that years of schooling, \(S\), may be related to the number of siblings (brothers and sisters), \(SIBLINGS\), according to the relationship

\[\begin{equation*} S=\beta_{1}+\beta_{2}SIBLINGS+u \end{equation*}\]

She is prepared to test the null hypothesis \(H_0:\beta_{2}=0\) against the alternative hypothesis \(H_1:\beta_{2}\neq 0\) at the 5% and 1% levels. She has a sample of 60 observations.

The critical t values at the 5% and 1% significance level are 2.00 and 2.66 respectively. Undertake hypothesis tests for the following scenarios:

  1. \(\hat{\beta}_{2}=-0.20\), s.e.\((\hat{\beta}_{2})=0.07\)

  2. \(\hat{\beta}_{2}=-0.12\), s.e.\((\hat{\beta}_{2})=0.07\)

  3. \(\hat{\beta}_{2}=0.06\), s.e.\((\hat{\beta}_{2})=0.07\)

  4. \(\hat{\beta}_{2}=0.20\), s.e.\((\hat{\beta}_{2})=0.07\)

To test whether any of the coefficients provided above are statistically significant, we need to follow these steps:

  1. State the null and alternative hypotheses

  2. Select the significance level

  3. Select and calculate the test statistics

  4. Set the decision rule

  5. Make statistical decisions

Now we look at this question.

Step 1. We know the null hypothesis is \(H_0:\beta_{2}\)= and alternative hypothesis is \(H_1:\beta_{2}\neq\) .

Step 2. The significance levels are % and %.

Step 3: calculate the t-values, which measure how many standard errors is our coefficient away from zero.

\[\begin{equation*} t=\frac{\hat{\beta}_{2}-\beta_{2}^0}{s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{2})} \end{equation*}\]

Step 4: The decision rule is: If the absolute value of t-value is than the critical value, then we reject the null Hypothesis and our coefficient is statistically significant.

Please note:

  • Our test is two-tailed, so the non-rejection area has a left boundary of -2.00 at the 5% significance level and -2.66 at the 1% significance level. The right boundary is +2.00 for 5% and +2.66 for 1% significance level.

  • Looking at the critical values shows that to reject the null Hypothesis at a lower significance level, the t-value has to be greater than for a higher significance level! Therefore the non-rejection area at the 1% significance level is wider than at the 5% significance level.

  • If you can reject the \(H_0\) at the 1% significance level, you can always reject it also at the 5% significance level, but if you can reject it at the 5% level does not mean that you can also reject it at the 1% significance level!

  • To get full points in the coursework, ensure that you complete the 5 steps of Hypothesis testing.

Step 5: Make decisions

Step 1. We know the null hypothesis is \(H_0:\beta_{2}=0\) and alternative hypothesis is \(H_1:\beta_{2}\neq 0\).

Step 2. The significance levels are 5% and 1%.

Step 4: The decision rule is: If the absolute value of t-value is greater than the critical value, then we can reject the null Hypothesis and our coefficient is statistically significant.


Now we calculate the t-values in step 3 and undertake hypothesis tests for the following scenarios:

  1. \(\hat{\beta}_{2}=-0.20\), s.e.\((\hat{\beta}_{2})=0.07\)

Null hypothesis: \(H_0:\beta_{2} = 0\); Alternative hypothesis: \(H_1:\beta_{2}\neq 0\)

\(t=\frac{\hat{\beta}_{2}-\beta_{2}^0}{s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{2})} \approx\) (Fill in with three decimal places)

At the 1% level, the left critical value is (Fill in with two decimal places), so t-value falls into the left area, therefore we \(H_0\) at the 1% level.

Because we it at the 1% level, we already know that we can also it at the 5% level.

\(t=\frac{\hat{\beta}_{2}-\beta_{2}^0}{s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{2})} \approx -2.857\)

At the 1% level, the left critical value is -2.66, so t-value falls into the left reject area, therefore we reject \(H_0\) at the 1% level.

Because we reject it at the 1% level, we already know that we can also reject it at the 5% level.


  1. \(\hat{\beta}_{2}=-0.12\), s.e.\((\hat{\beta}_{2})=0.07\)

Null hypothesis: \(H_0:\beta_{2} = 0\); Alternative hypothesis: \(H_1:\beta_{2}\neq 0\)

\(t=\frac{\hat{\beta}_{2}-\beta_{2}^0}{s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{2})} \approx\) (Fill in with three decimal places)

At the 5% level, this t-value falls within area, therefore we \(H_0\) at the 5 % level.

As we \(H_0\) at the 5% level, we already know that we also cannot reject it at the 1% level!

\(t=\frac{\hat{\beta}_{2}-\beta_{2}^0}{s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{2})} \approx -1.714\)

At the 5% level, this t-value falls within non-rejection area, therefore we cannot reject \(H_0\) at the 5% level.

As we cannot reject \(H_0\) at the 5% level, we already know that we also cannot reject it at the 1% level!


  1. \(\hat{\beta}_{2}=0.06\), s.e.\((\hat{\beta}_{2})=0.07\)

Null hypothesis: \(H_0:\beta_{2} = 0\); Alternative hypothesis: \(H_1:\beta_{2}\neq 0\)

\(t=\frac{\hat{\beta}_{2}-\beta_{2}^0}{s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{2})} \approx\) (Fill in with three decimal places)

At the 5% level, t-value falls within area, therefore we \(H_0\) at the 5% level.

As we \(H_0\) at the 5% level, we already know that we also cannot reject it at the 1% level!

\(t=\frac{\hat{\beta}_{2}-\beta_{2}^0}{s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{2})} \approx 0.857\)

At the 5% level, t-value falls within non-rejection area, therefore we cannot reject \(H_0\) at the 5% level.

As we cannot reject \(H_0\) at the 5% level, we already know that we also cannot reject it at the 1% level!


  1. \(\hat{\beta}_{2}=0.20\), s.e.\((\hat{\beta}_{2})=0.07\)

Null hypothesis: \(H_0:\beta_{2} = 0\); Alternative hypothesis: \(H_1:\beta_{2}\neq 0\)

\(t=\frac{\hat{\beta}_{2}-\beta_{2}^0}{s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{2})} \approx\) (Fill in with three decimal places)

At the 1% level,the right critical value is (Fill in with two decimal places), so t-value falls within area, therefore we \(H_0\) at the 1 % level.

Because we it at the 1 % level, we already know that we can also it at the 5% level.

\(t=\frac{\hat{\beta}_{2}-\beta_{2}^0}{s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{2})} \approx 2.857\)

At the 1% level,the right critical value is 2.66, so t-value falls within reject area, therefore we reject \(H_0\) at the 1% level.

Because we reject it at the 1% level, we already know that we can also reject it at the 5% level.


Question 2

The number of cigarettes smoked per day is regressed on the price of cigarettes per pack in USD. Sample size \(n=807\).

  1. Interpret the intercept and the coefficient of the independent variable.

  • Interpretation of the price of cigarettes coefficient: USD price increase would decrease the number of cigarettes smoked by (Fill in with five decimal places).

  • Interpretation of the constant: If the cigarette price per pack was , then individuals would smoke on average (Fill in with five decimal places) cigarettes.

  • Interpretation of the price of cigarettes coefficient: 1 USD price increase would decrease the number of cigarettes smoked by 0.03297.

  • Interpretation of the constant: If the cigarette price per pack was 0, then individuals would smoke on average 10.67457 cigarettes.


  1. Write down the test hypotheses for testing the significance of the intercept and coefficient.

\(H_0:\beta_{1}=\), \(H_1:\beta_{1}\neq\)

\(H_0:\beta_{2}=\), \(H_1:\beta_{2}\neq\)

\(H_0:\beta_{1}=0\), \(H_1:\beta_{1}\neq 0\)

\(H_0:\beta_{2}=0\), \(H_1:\beta_{2}\neq 0\)


  1. Calculate t-statistics for the intercept and the coefficient of cigarette prices. The critical t-value at the 5% significance level is 1.96.
  • Intercept: \(t-value = \frac{\hat{\beta}_{1}-\beta_{1}^0}{s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{1})} \approx\) (Fill in with three decimal places) < \(t_{crit,5\%}= 1.96\)

We cannot reject \(H_0\). The intercept is statistically .

  • Cigprice: \(t-value = \frac{\hat{\beta}_{2}-\beta_{2}^0}{s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{2})} \approx\) (Fill in with three decimal places) > \(t_{crit,5\%}=-1.96\)

We cannot reject \(H_0\). The coefficient of cigarette price is statistically .

  • Intercept: \(t-value = \frac{\hat{\beta}_{1}-\beta_{1}^0}{s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{1})}=\approx 1.729\) < \(t_{crit,5\%}= 1.96\)

We cannot reject \(H_0\). The intercept is statistically insignificant.

  • Cigprice: \(t-value = \frac{\hat{\beta}_{2}-\beta_{2}^0}{s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{2})} \approx -0.323\) > \(t_{crit,5\%}=-1.96\)

We cannot reject \(H_0\). The coefficient of cigarette price is statistically insignificant.


Question 3

Calculate the 95% confidence interval for the intercept as well as the coefficient of cigarette prices using the R output in Question 2.

The formula for calculating the confidence interval for the intercept is \[\begin{equation*} \hat{\beta}_{1}-s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{1}) \times t_{crit,5\%} \leq \beta_{1} \leq \hat{\beta}_{1}+s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{1}) \times t_{crit,5\%} \end{equation*}\]

The regression output shows that the point estimate \(\hat{\beta}_{1}\) is (Fill in with five decimal places) and its standard error \(s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{1})\) is (Fill in with five decimal places).

The formula for calculating the confidence interval for the cigarette coefficient is

\[\begin{equation*} \hat{\beta}_{2}-s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{2}) \times t_{crit,5\%} \leq \beta_{2} \leq \hat{\beta}_{2}+s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{2}) \times t_{crit,5\%} \end{equation*}\]

The regression output shows that the point estimate \(\hat{\beta_{2}}\) is (Fill in with five decimal places) and its standard error \(s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{2})\) is (Fill in with five decimal places).

The regression output shows that the point estimate \(\hat{\beta}_{1}\) is 10.67457 and its standard error \(s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{1})\) is 6.17296.

\[\begin{equation*} 10.67457-6.17296 \times 1.96 \leq \beta_{1} \leq 10.67457+6.17296 \times 1.96 \end{equation*}\]

The regression output shows that the point estimate \(\hat{\beta_{2}}\) is -0.03297 and its standard error \(s.e.(\hat{\beta}_{2})\) is 0.10206.

\[\begin{equation*} -0.03297-0.10206 \times 1.96 \leq \beta_{2} \leq -0.03297+ 0.10206 \times 1.96 \end{equation*}\]
